narratives.question_text: How would you summarize ECON 110 05 for a fellow student? Would you recommend ECON 110 05 to another student? Why or why not?
comments: I enjoyed the course this year and think it will be even better in future iterations. It's mainly a focus on 20th century responses to failures of the Enlightenment, which are really interesting and relevant to today's world. It's a lot of reading/writing, but Prof. Wetters/Jan were really helpful and you can certainly get through it with a bit of hard work and reaching out for assistance. Class lagged at times, but it was a small seminar with an even smaller contingent willing to participate so that was as responsible as anything for that. Survey courses are inherently frustrating, but this offers a lot of interesting perspectives on things that are important/interesting but are generally not covered in depth at Yale. Would definitely give a thumbs up.
A wonderful tour de force through Enlightenment thought, continuing the legacy into the present!
